Metastatic rectal carcinoma.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Joyner is 31 years old.  Pertinent oncologic history:
1.  Intermittent rectal bleeding for six-months but more so in spring 2010.
2.  He developed back pain, which prompted him to seek medical evaluation.  His stool has changed with an increase in frequency and decrease in caliber.
3.  March 29, 2010:  Colonoscopy positive for numerous polyps throughout the colon as well as circumferential mass at 15-cm.  The biopsy was moderately to poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma.
4.  Patient came to the Wise Sanitarium Number 1 Memorial Hospital and was seen in Gastroenterology April 7, 2010.  Repeat colonoscopy with EUS confirmed a nonobstructing rectal carcinoma, and in addition, there were numerous retroperitoneal nodes as high as 50 cm seen between the sigmoid colon and the aortic bifurcation at 25 cm.  On biopsy, these were positive for malignancy.  He underwent upper endoscopy also and had multiple polyps in his stomach.
5.  He was seen by Dr. Dale Miller of Colorectal Surgery, who did not feel he was a surgical candidate at this time.  He was then seen by Dr. Jessie Boles, who felt the extent of the nodal disease was too much for radiation at this time.
He is referred to West Tennessee Tuberculosis Hospital.  He does have discomfort in his back, and he has occasional rectal bleeding.  He otherwise is active and feels well.

